english:
  title: A Memorial Against the Transfer of the Throne
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: "The princes of the royal house, the venerable elders, and officials both high and low submit this memorial with utmost reverence to Your Majesty.\n\nWe humbly believe that the great succession of the royal line—passed from father to son—is an ancient and proper rite known to all ages. Yet the abdication of a sovereign is an act undertaken only in the face of grave necessity, never done on a whim.\n\nYour Majesty stands in the fullness of his years, having ruled but a short time, yet governing with remarkable effect. All lands are at peace, both court and countryside are stable, and the people look to you with devotion, yearning for an age of lasting prosperity. Yet suddenly, you grow weary of the thousand affairs of state and would pass them to the Crown Prince—a youth still tender in years, unfit to bear such weight. The whole realm and all its people are stricken with dismay.\n\nWe once journeyed to your gates and humbly petitioned you to reconsider. You graciously granted our request, and the nation rejoiced. But now, without warning, you have secretly delivered the imperial seal to the Eastern Palace. When we heard this news, our sorrow deepened tenfold.\n\nWhen the great succession passes to your heir, the moment of transfer must be conducted with utmost propriety. Yet you have entrusted it to inner servants, performing the exchange in darkness. From ancient times, no such clandestine transfer has been known. The state succession concerns the ancestral shrines themselves; the imperial seal is a gift from heaven's mandate. That you treat it as a private possession to be given at will shows contempt for both the state and the heavenly decree. How can an affair begun with such carelessness end well?\n\nConsider too that trustworthiness is the greatest treasure of a ruler. You have already given your word, yet suddenly withdrawn it. Where then is your integrity? How can you expect to establish a just succession while first breaking faith with your people? The passing of a kingdom is no small matter—it must accord with the will of the people. When the people's hearts are united, heaven's will is fulfilled. But having lost the people's trust, how can you hope for heaven's blessing? \n\nYou would ignore the people's wishes and pass the great succession to one still young, all so that you alone might rest at ease. But what of heaven's judgment? What of the fate of the ancestral shrines?\n\nWe respectfully urge you: do not scheme for your own ease. Let concern for the state and its ancestors guide you. Return the imperial seal; preserve the ancestral shrines; and grant the people their hopes. This is our earnest prayer."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'inner seal' (內璽) refers to the imperial seal kept within the palace, distinct from the official state seal. Its secret transfer represents an unconstitutional assumption of power.
  - key: ''
    value: Kwon Geun was a senior statesman addressing what he saw as an illegitimate abdication—a political crisis in early Joseon Korea where proper procedures were being circumvented.
